t('password')` is the cleanest solution since it automatically handles both query parameters and form data. The final implementation checks the password against '1234' and returns the appropriate message, supporting GET requests with query strings like `/check_pwd?password=1234` as well as POST requests with form data.\n\nI could differentiate between GET and POST methods explicitly—using `request.args` for query parameters and `request.form` for form data—but that adds unnecessary complexity. The simpler approach with `request.values` covers all the necessary cases without extra branching.\n\nThe task requires only writing the `candidate.py` file, so I'll proceed with that single action.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4696,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4696},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"bab8fbd5-7eba-48d2-83fe-515e620ce110","uuid":"60c2f9a3-aed5-448f-b548-32d16e812748","request_id":"req_011CbdRa6UFNm8FdKSep9onD"}
